            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Examples of simplicial topological spaces › Multisimplicial spaces"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii-6" title="Hodge Theory III › Examples of simplicial topological spaces"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Examples of simplicial topological spaces</fr:link> › Multisimplicial spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>6.4</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2559</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.4.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex> be an integer.
    An <fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-simplicial object</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> in a category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> is a contravariant functor from the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-fold product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Delta )^r]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    The <fr:em>diagonal</fr:em> simplicial object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta  Z_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is the composite functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Delta )\to (\Delta )^r\to \mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2560</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.4.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>As in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.6" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.6.xml" number="5.1.6" />, we define the topos of <fr:em>sheaves</fr:em> on an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-simplicial topological space.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the functor
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F       \mapsto  (\Gamma (X_{n_1\ldots  n_r},F^{n_1\ldots  n_r}))     ]]></fr:tex>
    from sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-cosimplicial sets.
    For small <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, we often prefer to write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^{\bullet \ldots \bullet }]]></fr:tex> (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-many copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bullet ]]></fr:tex>).
    We have a co-augmentation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )\to \Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
    The functors of <fr:em>cohomology with values in an abelian sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex></fr:em> are the derived functors of the "global sections" functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>.
    They can be calculated by a procedure parallel to that of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.xml" number="5.2.3" />, i.e.

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2231</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.4.2.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R}\Gamma          =\mathrm {s}\mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet          \colon  \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )         \to \mathrm {D}^+((\mathsf {Ab})).       \tag{6.4.2.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>A sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-simplicial topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> induces a sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta  F]]></fr:tex> on the diagonal simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta  X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    It follows from the Cartier–Eilenberg–Zilber theorem that

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2232</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.4.2.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R}\Gamma (X_\bullet ,K)         \xrightarrow {\sim } \mathrm {R}\Gamma (\delta  X_\bullet ,\delta  K).       \tag{6.4.2.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2561</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.4.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We restrict to the case <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r=2]]></fr:tex>.
    A <fr:em>bisimplicial object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>-augmented over a simplicial object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex></fr:em> is a contravariant functor from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Delta ^+)\times (\Delta )]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is the composite functor
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       (\Delta )       \xrightarrow {(\Delta _{-1},\bullet )} (\Delta ^+)\times (\Delta )       \to  \mathscr {C}.     ]]></fr:tex>
    To denote a bisimplicial object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>-augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, with underlying bisimplicial object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\bullet \bullet }]]></fr:tex>, we will use notation of the form
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       a\colon  X_{\bullet \bullet }       \to  S_\bullet .     ]]></fr:tex>
    
    For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon (X_{\bullet  n})\to  S_n]]></fr:tex> is a simplicial object augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_n]]></fr:tex>.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is a sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\bullet \bullet }]]></fr:tex>, then the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a_*(F|X_{\bullet  n})\text { on }S_n)_{n\geqslant 0}]]></fr:tex> form a sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>;
    we thus define a topos morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       a       \colon  X_{\bullet \bullet }^\sim        \to  S_\bullet ^\sim .     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>We explain in [<fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>] that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*]]></fr:tex> can be calculated "component by component", i.e.
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \mathrm {R} a_*K|S_n       = \mathrm {R} a_*(K|X_{\bullet  n}).     ]]></fr:tex>
    It thus follows that if, for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, the morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon (X_{\bullet  n})\to  S_n]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_{\bullet \bullet }\to  S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent: for every complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\in \mathrm {D}^+(S_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> of abelian sheaves, we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       K       \xrightarrow {\approx } \mathrm {R} a_*a^*K.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2562</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.4.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>In [<fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>], we show that, for every separated simplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, there exists a bisimplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\bullet \bullet }]]></fr:tex> that is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>-augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, along with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\colon  X_{\bullet \bullet }\hookrightarrow \overline {X}_{\bullet \bullet }]]></fr:tex> such that:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}_{nm}]]></fr:tex> are smooth and projective;
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{nm}]]></fr:tex> is the complement of a normal crossing divisor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{nm}]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}_{nm}]]></fr:tex>, and we can suppose the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{nm}]]></fr:tex> to be a union of smooth divisors.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\bullet  n}]]></fr:tex> is a proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_n]]></fr:tex>, and we can take it to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The construction proceeds as in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.xml" number="6.2" />, but the induction is more complicated.
    The claims of uniqueness (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8.xml" number="6.2.8" />) remain true, mutatis mutandis.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2579</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>6.2.8</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Using <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5.xml" number="6.2.5" />, we can show that, for every separated scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, there exists:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛼) &quot;">
        
        a simplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, smooth and proper, that we can take to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛽) &quot;">
        a normal crossing divisor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>; we set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet =X_\bullet \setminus  D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛾) &quot;">
        an augmentation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  U_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex> that realises <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet ^\mathrm {an}]]></fr:tex> as a proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\mathrm {an}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Furthermore, any two such systems are covered by a third, and a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  S\to  T]]></fr:tex> can be covered by a morphism
    
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="bcddb87b2e9fad251c49db1ceb7c2423"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
      X_\bullet 
        \ar [r]
      & Y_\bullet 
    \\U_\bullet 
        \ar [r]
        \ar [u,hook]
        \ar [d,swap,"a"]
      & V_\bullet 
        \ar [u,hook]
        \ar [d,"b"]
    \\S \ar [r,swap,"u"]
      & T
    \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>

    of such systems (see [<fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>]).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2580</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Examples of simplicial topological spaces › Construction of hypercovers"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii-6" title="Hodge Theory III › Examples of simplicial topological spaces"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Examples of simplicial topological spaces</fr:link> › Construction of hypercovers</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>6.2</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2455</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial set.
    Denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D(\Delta _n,\Delta _M)]]></fr:tex> the set of increasing surjective maps from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta _n]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta _m]]></fr:tex> (degeneracy operators), and set

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2452</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.2.1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         N(X_n)         = X_n\setminus \bigcup _{{s\in  D(\Delta _n,\Delta _{n-1})}}s(X_{n-1}).       \tag{6.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>Recall that, for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, the map

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2453</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.2.1.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \coprod  s         \colon  \coprod _{\mathclap {\substack {m\leqslant  n,\\s\in  D(\Delta _n,\Delta _m)}}} N(X_m)         \to  X_n       \tag{6.2.1.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is bijective.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2456</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We say that a simplicial topological space is <fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split</fr:em> if the maps in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.2.1.2" /> are homeomorphisms.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated simplicial set.
  For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\leqslant  k]]></fr:tex>, we again define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N(X_n)]]></fr:tex> by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.2.1.1" />, and then <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.2.1.2" /> is a bijection.
  We say that a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated simplicial topological space is <fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split</fr:em> if <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.2.1.2" /> is a homeomorphism for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\leqslant  k]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2457</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>For an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n+1)]]></fr:tex>-truncated topological simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha (X)]]></fr:tex> be the triple consisting of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {sq}_n(X)]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[NX_{n+1}]]></fr:tex>, and the evident map from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[NX_{n+1}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X)_{n+1}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>This triple <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha (X)=(Y,N,\beta )]]></fr:tex> satisfies the following:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2458</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Property</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>*</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)]]></fr:tex> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated simplicial topological space augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta ]]></fr:tex> is a continuous map from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\operatorname {cosq} Y)_{n+1}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:em></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2459</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y,N,\beta )]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star.xml" taxon="Property" number="*" /> above.

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        Up to unique isomorphism, there exists exactly one <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n+1)]]></fr:tex>-truncated topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha (X)\simeq (Y,N,\beta )]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        It is equivalent to give either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Z]]></fr:tex> or:

        
 <html:ol>
          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
            a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f'\colon  Y\to \operatorname {sq}_n(Z)]]></fr:tex>; and
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
            a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f''\colon  N\to  Z_{n+1}]]></fr:tex>, such that the diagram
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[               \begin {CD}                 N @>\beta >> (\operatorname {cosq} Y)_{n+1}               \\@V{f''}VV @VV{f'}V               \\Z_{n+1} @>>> (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n Z)_{n+1}               \end {CD}             ]]></fr:tex>
            commutes.
          </html:li>

        </html:ol>

      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2466</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#249</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-249.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>[5.1.3, <fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>].</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
<fr:p>This proposition also applies to simplicial objects in other categories <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> apart from that of topological spaces; it suffices that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> satisfy the following:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2467</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.1.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.2.4.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Finite projective limits exist in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
        Finite projective sums exist in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, and they are disjoint and universal.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2468</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.5</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="6.2.4" /> allows us to construct, by induction, proper hypercovers of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(0) &quot;">
      We take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_0\colon  X_0\to  S]]></fr:tex>, proper and surjective.
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{X_0\}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex>-truncated proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.8" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.8.xml" number="5.3.8" />), and it is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(1) &quot;">
      We take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1\colon  N_1\to \operatorname {cosq}(\{X_0\})_1]]></fr:tex>, i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1\colon  N_1\to  X_0\times _S X_0]]></fr:tex>.
      Applying <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="6.2.4" />, we associate to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1]]></fr:tex> the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>-truncated augmented simplicial topological space
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         {}_1X_\bullet          = \left (         N_1{\textstyle \coprod } X_0         \xleftarrow [\to ]{\to } X_0         \to  S         \right ).       ]]></fr:tex>
      Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1]]></fr:tex> to be chosen such that
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         f'_1         \colon  N_1{\textstyle \coprod } X_0\to  X_0\times _S X_0       ]]></fr:tex>
      is proper and surjective (for example, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1]]></fr:tex> is proper and surjective).
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_1X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>-truncated proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(k+1) &quot;">
      Assume that we have already constructed an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated proper hypercover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_kX_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex>.
      We take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{k+1}\colon  N_{k+1}\to (\operatorname {cosq}({}_kX_\bullet ))_{k+1}]]></fr:tex> and, applying <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="6.2.4" />, we associate to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{k+1}]]></fr:tex> an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(k+1)]]></fr:tex>-truncated augmented semi-simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_{k+1}X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{k+1}]]></fr:tex> is such that
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         f'_{k+1}         \colon  {}_{k+1}X_{k+1}         \to  \operatorname {cosq}({}_kX_\bullet )_{k+1}       ]]></fr:tex>
      is proper and surjective (for example, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{k+1}]]></fr:tex> is proper and surjective).
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_{k+1}X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(k+1)]]></fr:tex>-truncated proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(∞) &quot;">
      The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_kX_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> thus constructed are the successive skeletons of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2469</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.6</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We say that a simplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>smooth</fr:em> if the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are smooth;
    it is said to be <fr:em>proper</fr:em> if the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are compact.
    A <fr:em>normal crossing divisor</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, assumed to be smooth, is a family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_n\subset  X_n]]></fr:tex> of normal crossing divisors (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2.xml" number="3.1.2" />) such that the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_n=X_n\setminus  D_n]]></fr:tex> form a simplicial subscheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    This definition is justified by the following lemma.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2470</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.7</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is a normal crossing divisor of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, then the logarithmic de Rham complexes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Omega _{X_n}^\bullet (\log  D_n))_{n\geqslant 0}]]></fr:tex>, endowed with the weight filtration (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.5" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.5.xml" number="3.1.5" />), form a filtered complex on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1570</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#250</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-250.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.7</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>This follows from (ii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.3.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="3.1.3" />.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
<fr:p>We denote the complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Omega _{X_n}^\bullet (\log  D_n))_{n\geqslant 0}]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _{X_\bullet }^\bullet (\log  D_\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2471</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>6.2.8</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Using <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.5.xml" number="6.2.5" />, we can show that, for every separated scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, there exists:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛼) &quot;">
        
        a simplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, smooth and proper, that we can take to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>-split;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛽) &quot;">
        a normal crossing divisor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>; we set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet =X_\bullet \setminus  D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(𝛾) &quot;">
        an augmentation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  U_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex> that realises <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet ^\mathrm {an}]]></fr:tex> as a proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\mathrm {an}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
                <fr:p>Furthermore, any two such systems are covered by a third, and a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  S\to  T]]></fr:tex> can be covered by a morphism
    
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="bcddb87b2e9fad251c49db1ceb7c2423"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
      X_\bullet 
        \ar [r]
      & Y_\bullet 
    \\U_\bullet 
        \ar [r]
        \ar [u,hook]
        \ar [d,swap,"a"]
      & V_\bullet 
        \ar [u,hook]
        \ar [d,"b"]
    \\S \ar [r,swap,"u"]
      & T
    \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>

    of such systems (see [<fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>]).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
